In this series we will learn the concepts of DevOps from a perspective of developers. How can these concepts help us be better developers and managers in our day to day jobs. In a startup you might need to fill the shoes of a DevOps, in a big company you might need to communicate with a DevOps team that has wildly different ideas.

We will gain a different perspective and understanding of the entire process by leaving our comfort zone and focusing on the wider picture. We will learn about different disciplines such as platform engineering and so much more.

In the first installment we discuss version control. As developers, we see it as a tool to collaborate and save our code. To track our mistakes and changes. In this video we learn why it's a crucial nexus point with the DevOps team and how we can work better to enable that.

videoTitle: What Does A DevOps Engineer Do? #salesforcetestingguy  ft. @TrainWithShubham
videoDescription:
A DevOps engineer serves as a pivotal link between development and operations teams, fostering seamless collaboration and communication to optimize the software delivery lifecycle.

At the core of a DevOps engineer's role is the establishment and maintenance of CI/CD pipelines, ensuring the continuous integration and deployment of software updates. This accelerates the release of new features and fixes, ultimately reducing the time required for delivering impactful changes.

In summary, the collaborative efforts and automation prowess of a DevOps engineer create an environment conducive to rapid and high-quality software delivery, empowering organizations to stay competitive in the dynamic landscape of software development.

videoTitle: 8 DevOps Best Practices You MUST KNOW in 2024 | Essential DevOps Best Practices 2024
videoDescription:
In this comprehensive video, we will cover various key aspects of DevOps best practices. We'll start with an insightful introduction, providing you with a solid foundation of understanding DevOps and its significance in the modern IT landscape. Then, we'll explore the criticality of cultural change and how it plays a pivotal role in fostering a collaborative and innovation-driven work environment.

Next, we'll dive into version control and trunk-based development, showcasing how these practices streamline code management and facilitate seamless collaboration among developers. Automation will also take center stage, as we discuss the benefits of automating repetitive tasks, enabling faster deployment and reducing manual errors.

Moving forward, we'll shed light on continuous integration and continuous delivery, two pivotal practices that ensure frequent code integration and deployment. Monitoring and feedback will be explored as well, emphasizing the vital role of real-time feedback loops and continuous monitoring in maintaining software quality and performance.

Moreover, we'll delve into the realm of DevSecOps, highlighting the importance of integrating security into every stage of the development process. Building secure applications is paramount in an age where cyber threats are constantly evolving.

We'll also touch upon the significance of identical and reproducible environments, discussing how environment consistency leads to smoother deployments and more reliable software. Lastly, we'll emphasize the significance of documentation, highlighting how well-documented procedures and code enable efficient collaboration and knowledge sharing.

Join us on this insightful journey as we unpack the essential DevOps best practices for 2023. Make sure to subscribe to our channel and hit the notification bell to stay updated with the latest trends and advancements in the world of DevOps!

videoTitle: Beyond DevOps: The rise of full-stack platform engineering | Peter Birkholm-Buch
videoDescription:
In this talk, Peter explores the evolution of #DevOps and introduces the concept of full-stack #platformengineering. While DevOps promised to bridge the gap between development and operations, it often resulted in Ops teams scripting infrastructure without applying key software engineering principles. Platform engineering takes this further by treating infrastructure as a product, raising the abstraction level, and enabling developers with scalable, reusable solutions. Peter will explain how they made this shift at Carlsberg and why the future of infrastructure lies in full-stack platform engineers who can think like developers and build for the future.

----

About the speaker:

Peter Birkholm Buch is a senior technology leader with over 35 years of experience in software engineering, architecture, and cloud computing. As the Head of Software Engineering at Carlsberg, Peter leads a global team of 75 engineers across Portugal, Malaysia, and the Philippines. His expertise lies in driving innovation through cloud-based solutions, platform engineering, and the alignment of DevOps practices. Peter is passionate about improving #DeveloperExperience and ensuring compliance and governance across large-scale engineering teams. He has a unique ability to blend strategy with hands-on technical leadership, making him a sought-after speaker and thought leader in the industry.

----

videoTitle: Six real-world examples of how teams adopt DevOps |  David Rutter&Ronnie Hilmersson
videoDescription:
Track talk at The DEVOPS Conference - Stockholm, on October 2023: So you've merged Dev and Ops, but what comes next? Six real-world examples of how teams adopt DevOps

In 2016, WirelessCar embarked on its DevOps journey by merging Development and Operations, marking the start of a transformative process. At The DEVOPS Conference, David Rutter
(Organizational Change Manager) and Ronnie Hilmersson (Scrum Master) from WirelessCar present the practical insights from this journey, shared by various teams within WirelessCar's 500-person development and product delivery organization. They explore the diverse aspects of DevOps and illustrate their implementation through real examples.

Discover how shared responsibilities, leveraging the DevOps Health Radar, utilizing DORA metrics, and enabling enabler teams drove our progress. Learn how WirelessCar balanced increased deployment frequency with unwavering quality (as well as explore Susan Wheelan's IMDG and GDQ tools--instrumental in forging high-performing teams.) Additionally, David and Ronnie outline the organizational support provided to facilitate DevOps adoption while ensuring compliance, security, and quality standards. #DevOps #TheDevOpsConference

---

Speakers: David Rutter - Agile and Tech Leader, who has worked as a Scrum Master, Developer and Organizational Change Manager.

Ronnie Hilmersson - Ronnie has been working with DevOps culture, agile, and lean for several years in different companies and in different roles. He started in WirelessCar in 2020 as a Scrum Master, and very soon, he also had the chance to help out with the DevOps culture in the company.

---

videoTitle: Stop using Read-Host and do this instead #powershell  #devops  #scripting
videoDescription:
Stop using Read-Host and do this instead:

Read-Host has limitations. 

- You cannot pass information to it 
- You cannot validate what the user provided
- It always stops the script

There is a better way - use parameters instead.

- Control the type of input
- Make it mandatory or optional
- Pass argument from the command line
- or prompt the user to provide an argument, when required and not passed

In this short video, I'll show you how to implement simple parameters and how to use them.

Would you like to learn more about the parameters?

videoTitle: Practical DevOps: Continuous Delivery vs Continuous Deployment
videoDescription:
Continuous integration, deployment, and delivery are like vectors with the same direction but different magnitudes. Their goal is the same: to make our software development and release process faster and more robust.

The key difference between the three is in the scope of automation applied. What confuses people new to the field is that they are not mutually exclusive, but include each other, like Russian dolls.

videoTitle: Empower Your DevOps with Architecture-Driven IaC & InnerSourcing | Full Office Hours Keynote #07
videoDescription:
In our 7th Office Hours, we introduced key updates designed to make infrastructure management more transparent, scalable, and collaborative. This session focused on how architecture-driven Infrastructure as Code (IaC) and InnerSourcing can transform the way DevOps teams build, share, and manage infrastructure at scale.

Key Takeaways:
InnerSourcing with Custom Terraform Modules – We introduced custom Terraform modules built on InnerSourcing principles, enabling teams to collaborate and contribute to a shared infrastructure codebase. By applying open-source methodologies within an organization, DevOps teams gain flexibility, efficiency, and reusability while reducing silos.

View Permissions in User Management – Security and governance are critical in modern DevOps workflows. This feature allows granular access control, ensuring that only the right people have visibility into specific resources, balancing security with operational efficiency.

The Future of Infrastructure Collaboration – As organizations scale, having a decentralized but structured approach to infrastructure management is key. We discussed how InnerSourcing, Infrastructure as Code (IaC), and DevOps best practices can help teams move faster while maintaining control.

Keywords: DevOps, InnerSourcing, Infrastructure as Code, IaC, Terraform, cloud automation, platform engineering, security and governance, DevOps collaboration, access management, software development

3:15 - InnerSourcing with Custom Terraform Modules
